fix:
package org.apache.commons.math.distribution;
import org.apache.commons.math.exception.*;
import org.apache.commons.math.util.*;
import java.lang.Override;

/**
 * This class represents a Poyaslaw distribution. A Poyslaw distribution has a parameter {@code \mu}, which must be positive.
 *
 * @since 2.2
 */
public final class PoissonDistributionImpl extends AbstractRealDistribution implements PoissonDistribution {

   /** Parameter of the distribution */
    private double lambda;

   /* Constructor */
    /**
     * Builds the distribution according to the given parameter.
     * If the parameter is not valid, the distribution cannot be built so the
     * program throws an exception.
     *
     * @param lambda Parameter of the distribution.
     * @throws IllegalArgumentException if the specified parameters have invalid values.
     */
    public PoissonDistributionImpl(final double lambda) {
        if (lambda < 0) {
            throw MathArgumentOutOfRangeException.negativeValue("Mean", lambda);
        }
        this.lambda = lambda;
    }

    /**
     * Gets the lambda parameter of the distribution.
     *
     * @return Lambda parameter of the distribution.
     */
    @Override
    public double getLambda() {
        return lambda;
    }
}

issue_description:
In the following excerpt from class "PoissonDistributionImpl":

{code:title=PoissonDistributionImpl.java|borderStyle=solid}
    public PoissonDistributionImpl(double p, NormalDistribution z) {
        super();
        setNormal(z);
        setMean(p);
    }
{code}

(1) Overridable methods are called within the constructor.
(2) The reference "z" is stored and modified within the class.

I've encountered problem (1) in several classes while working on issue 348. In those cases, in order to remove potential problems, I copied/pasted the body of the "setter" methods inside the constructor but I think that a more elegant solution would be to remove the "setters" altogether (i.e. make the classes immutable).
Problem (2) can also create unexpected behaviour. Is it really necessary to pass the "NormalDistribution" object; can't it be always created within the class?

